 D. H. Lawrence.Key FeaturesRewrites standard assumptions about John Middleton Murry's relationships with Katherine Mansfield and D. H. LawrenceProvides intertextual readings of fiction by Mansfield, Lawrence and MurryConsiders Murry's controversial role in the dissemination of modernist critical positionsExplores marginalisation and centrality in the creation of the modernist canon  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY COLLECTIONS / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000z97831107804680 cprintz978074864148240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978074864366040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780748643660423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780748643660/original  a978-3-11-078046-8  Edinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK